"title": "7402: offerings",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "7402",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>Anything offered up to God by human beings, including sacrificial offerings. A distinction can be made between offerings which involve the taking of life and other gifts made to God.</p>\n<h2>Sacrificial offerings as a sign of gratitude or repentance</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen4:4\">GEN 4:4</a></strong>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps107:22\">PSA 107:22</a></strong></p>\n<h2>Tithes were a regular form of offering</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen28:20-Gen28:22\">GEN 28:20–28:22</a></strong>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev27:30\">LEV 27:30</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen14:20\">GEN 14:20</a></p>\n<h2>Part of every harvest was given as a freewill offering to God</h2>\n<p>As firstfruits:\n <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod22:29\">EXO 22:29</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num18:12\">NUM 18:12</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut18:4\">DEU 18:4</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Neh10:35\">NEH 10:35</a>; \n<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev19:23-Lev19:25\">LEV 19:23–19:25</a> <em>Fruit from a tree could not be eaten until the fifth year</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev23:38\">LEV 23:38</a> <em>Extra gifts were offered on the Sabbath.</em></p>\n<h2>Offerings and the tabernacle</h2>\n<h3>For its construction</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod25:1-Exod25:2\">EXO 25:1–25:2</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod35:5\">EXO 35:5</a></p>\n<h3>At its dedication</h3>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num7:2-Num7:3\">NUM 7:2–7:3</a></p>\n<h2>Offerings and Solomon's temple</h2>\n<h3>David's personal gift</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr29:2-1Chr29:5\">1CH 29:2–29:5</a></p>\n<h3>Offerings for upkeep and restoration</h3>\n<p>In the reign of Joash:\n <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs12:4-2Kgs12:5\">2KI 12:4–12:5</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr24:8-2Chr24:12\">2CH 24:8–24:12</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs22:4-2Kgs22:6\">2KI 22:4–22:6</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr34:9-2Chr34:11\">2CH 34:9–34:11</a></p>\n<h2>Offerings and the second temple</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra3:5\">EZR 3:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra7:16\">EZR 7:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra8:24-Ezra8:30\">EZR 8:24–8:30</a></p>\n<h2>Offerings and Herod's temple</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark12:41-Mark12:43\">MRK 12:41–12:43</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke21:1-Luke21:3\">LUK 21:1–21:3</a> <em>The poor widow was participating in a regular practice</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke21:5\">LUK 21:5</a></p>\n<h2>Some offerings are not acceptable</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt5:23-Matt5:24\">MAT 5:23–5:24</a></strong> <em>Offerings are unacceptable unless the worshipper is reconciled to God.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen4:3-Gen4:5\">GEN 4:3–4:5</a> <em>Cain's offering was not accepted on account of his incorrect attitude.</em><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Amos4:4-Amos4:5\">AMO 4:4–4:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke18:12\">LUK 18:12</a>\n<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt23:23\">MAT 23:23</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke11:42\">LUK 11:42</a> <em>Meticulous tithing, without mercy or justice, is unacceptable.</em></p>\n<h2>Offerings in the future kingdom</h2>\n<h3>From the Gentile nations</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps76:11\">PSA 76:11</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa18:7\">ISA 18:7</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mal1:11\">MAL 1:11</a></p>\n<h3>From God's people</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek20:40\">EZK 20:40</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek44:30\">EZK 44:30</a></p>\n<h2>Gifts and offerings in the NT</h2>\n<h3>To help the needy</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts4:34-Acts4:35\">ACT 4:34–4:35</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts11:29-Acts11:30\">ACT 11:29–11:30</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor16:1-1Cor16:4\">1CO 16:1–16:4</a> <em>In several of his letters Paul mentions the freewill offering he was organising for poor Christians at Jerusalem</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb13:16\">HEB 13:16</a></p>\n<h3>To support God's servants</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Phil4:10-Phil4:18\">PHP 4:10–4:18</a></p>\n<h2>Offerings of praise</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb13:15\">HEB 13:15</a></p>\n<h2>God's people are themselves an offering to God</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer2:3\">JER 2:3</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jas1:18\">JAS 1:18</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:4\">REV 14:4</a></p>\n<h2>Offerings as ``Corban''</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark7:9-Mark7:13\">MRK 7:9–7:13</a></strong> <em>“Corban” is a technical Jewish religious term, meaning “something dedicated, especially on oath”. What Jesus Christ says implies that once the children had donated the amount they would have spent on their ageing parents for religious purposes, they were no longer responsible for their upkeep.</em></p>",
